radio_info.short: A University of Alberta student group requests that the Alberta government conduct a baseline health study of northern Alberta communities following an independent report that
radio_info.rest:
details the level of toxic chemicals downstream of Athabasca oil sands development.

The study, spearheaded by U of A water scientist Dr. David Schindler, reveals that the toxic chemical levels in the Athabasca River downstream from oil sands development are five times higher than official government estimates.

Due to the study’s December 7 release, the U of A-based group Stand with Fort Chipewyan is calling upon the Alberta government to conduct a more comprehensive follow-up to last February’s Alberta Health Services study.

Avnish nda, the group’s President, said that Dr. Schindler’s report has hurt the legitimacy of the government’s position on the issue surrounding the health of residents living in Fort Chipewyan, downstream along the Athabasca River.

The government denies that their health problems are linked to the environment, as well as that the oil sands projects upstream along the Athabasca are affecting the local environment.

“Although it’s irresponsible to jump to conclusions here, the government has a moral responsibility to uncover whether the development practices are indeed contributing to the health problems Fort Chipewyan faces,” he said, adding that that a baseline health study would establish the health of Northern Alberta residents today and allow for changes to be tracked in subsequent years.

This process can then identify whether health problems are increasing, and with other studies, identify what exactly is behind Fort Chipewyan’s situation.

“This has been requested by people in Aborigil and non-Aborigil communities alike in northern Alberta,” said nda. “Although last February’s AHS study established that Fort Chip’s cancer rates were at abnormally high, the government rejected the need to study what role the environment is playing in contributing to their serious health situation.”

About Stand With Fort Chipewyan

Stand with Fort Chipewyan is a non-partisan, campus advocacy organization located at the University of Alberta that was founded in January 2009. We are dedicated to raising awareness to concerns expressed by Fort Chipewyan residents, as well as lobbying the Alberta government to firmly establish the Athabasca oil sands’ effect on the health of neighbouring communities.

More information about Stand with Fort Chipewyan can be found at http://www.standwithfortchip.com.

radio_info.short: Since June 07 KAOS Radio has been promoting the traditional values which have been foundational in building a strong Wood Buffalo Region, through our vision
radio_info.rest:
of “Exposing Hope through Music talk and Action”. Our strong launch is a result of strong community support from people who believe in healthy media.

Given that many people spend approximately 6.2 – 7 hours a day engaged in media; it is becoming increasingly evident why healthy communities are paying more attention to the media this generation is consuming than ever before. Healthy media is part of a healthy community!

During the days the station caters to a 25-54 audience with its variety of Adult Contemporary music and friendly, more mature approach from its announce staff. In the evenings, KAOS 91.1reaches a slightly younger audience by playing a blend of Contemporary Hit & Top 40 Rock Radio music. Our research indicates that our average listener is approximately 34 year old Christian female

Featured artists include: Michael W. Smith, Mark Schultz, David Crowder, Matthew West, Stellar Kart, Relient K. Hillsong, Stephen Curtis Chapman, Chris Tomlin, MercyMe, Casting Crowns, Switchfoot, Daughtry, Newsboys Michael Buble, Jack Johnson and more.

KAOS Radio is a fun, relevant radio station with a positive message presented by a team of professional and entertaining announcers that can clearly identify and communicate with the station’s listeners.

KAOS is more than a radio station, it’s an initiative! We’re passionate about reaching, building and activating people to make a positive impact in the world. Unlike any other radio station in the market, our objective is not only to entertain and inform, but to provide listeners with a vital community resource that will open doors to help, hope, and life options. We “GIVE HELP an ADDRESS” by featuring social service agencies and helping connect them to people in need of their services.

KAOS RADIO is full of “social enterprise” through our KAOS community initiatives whichinclude partnerships with the education, business, social service, public health and religious sectors. We are involved in supporting local talent and Media Literacy designed to increase student awareness of media impact, and so much more. Some recent successes have been the KAOS KAFÉ, at InterPlay and the KAOS REPO CO, a street team which hit the streets of Fort McMurray during the summer of 2008.

We’re also dedicated to building our clients’ business. The KAOS sales culture is rooted in partnership and collaboration, where each customer relationship is approached as a joint venture aimed at achieving mutual satisfaction. We understand that when we meet the needs of our clients, our needs will be met as well! Christian radio is a proven marketing tool for Business as the faith community listen 2 times longer than regular listeners and are more loyal to the brand.

At KAOS we choose to serve all religious communities, and have worked closely in the past with the Islamic, the Catholic, the Christian community and many of the social service agencies in the Wood Buffalo region. There are approximately 30 faith based communities in the Fort McMurray area and they serve approximately 25,000 - 30,000 individuals in the greater Wood Buffalo Region who have a faith background.

KAOS prides itself on being the only station which offers a “family friendly guarantee” and non churched people listen as well. We have a strong appeal to the elderly, more established people in our community because of our talk programs with authors Charles Stanley and Chuck Swindol. We serve adult listeners as well as the younger demographic with our night programming.

One adult listener sent the following email:

Dear KAOS Staff: It is indeed a blessing to have a Christian radio station in the Mac.  I get to listen to 91.1 every AM and PM driving to and from work, and occasionally in the evenings.  So often, especially in the morning around 8:00 AM I’m rushing to work; my mind is rushing even faster than my driving, and I may not be particularly pleased with certain aspects of my job or life, responding to circumstance rather than truth.   Then along comes Dr. Stanley and jerks my mind back to reality and thinking true thoughts in line with God’s Word, and suddenly my day ’has a chance’ and my spirit is rejoicing.  As a High School teacher, believe me, that is important!

Shalom, Bro Ron

Why Faith Based Radio?

Simmons Market Research reports that 72% of Christian radio listeners prefer to buy from a business that advertises on a Christian radio station. And 62% say that they would "shop more at a known business if it advertised on Christian radio."
